\ examples/106-phi-pa-parametric-sweep.6th
\ Track 2.1 — Φ_PA family parametric sweep, look for phase transitions.
\
\ Question: do the substrate-readable Φ measures (phi-pa, phi-integ,
\ phi-bidir, phi-pa-witness) exhibit phase-transition behaviour — a
\ discontinuity or critical exponent — as a function of substrate
\ topological parameters?
\
\ Rationale: in physics and IIT-family consciousness measures, the
\ most interesting empirical signatures come from PHASE TRANSITIONS
\ (Tononi 2015 Φ-criticality, Mediano 2019 IIT critical exponents,
\ percolation theory).  If Φ_PA family inherits this, that would be
\ a substrate-derived prediction NOT designed in by the author —
\ direct counter to the "demos are tautological constructions"
\ critique.
\
\ Experimental design:
\
\   - Fixed substrate template: 11 nodes, observer at node 1
\   - Parameter k = number of out-edges from observer (0..9)
\   - Observer always has self-loop (so we measure scope effect, not
\     self-ref step)
\   - Each neighbour also has NGET loaded with its own out-degree
\     (canonical integration weight per phi-integ definition)
\   - For each k, build fresh substrate, measure all four Φ values
\
\ Predicted curves (analytic):
\
\   phi-pa(k)         = (k+1) · 1 · L_max          [linear in k]
\   phi-bidir(k)      = (k+1+IN) · 1 · L_max       [linear, no nonlin]
\   phi-integ(k)      = (k+1) · 1 · NSUM · L_max   [quadratic in k]
\   phi-pa-witness(k) = (k+1+W) · 1 · L_max        [linear in k]
\
\ Phase-transition test: scan for any DISCONTINUITY or NONLINEAR
\ break in the parametric curves.
\
\ Predicted outcome: all curves smooth (polynomial in k), NO
\ phase transition in this measure family.  If verified, this is
\ a substrate-derived BOUND on Φ_PA expressive power.

use prelude
use graph
use phi
use debug
use hedge

\ ============================================================
\ Substrate builder: parametric sweep over k = 0..9.
\
\ Per iteration k:
\   - RESET
\   - MARK 11 nodes (observer + 10 candidate neighbours)
\   - observer gets self-loop
\   - observer gets out-edges to first k neighbours
\   - each neighbour i gets its own out-edges to other neighbours
\     (chain pattern: neighbour i → neighbour i+1) to populate NGET
\     via OUT for phi-integ
\   - set each neighbour's NGET to its OUT count
\   - measure phi-pa, phi-bidir on the observer
\
\ Substrate state cells:
\   "obs"   — observer node id
\   "k"     — current sweep parameter
\   "phi-pa-vals"   — output (we just assert specific values)
\ ============================================================

\ k=0 baseline: observer + self-loop only, no out-edges to neighbours
RESET
MARK "obs" store
"obs" load "obs" load EDGE+           \ self-loop only
"obs" load OUT 1 assert-eq            \ self-loop counted in OUT
"obs" load phi-pa 10000 assert-eq     \ scope=1, self-ref=1
"obs" load phi-bidir 20000 assert-eq  \ OUT+IN: self-loop in both

\ ============================================================
\ k=1: observer + self-loop + one out-edge to a neighbour
\ ============================================================
RESET
MARK "obs" store
MARK "n1" store
"obs" load "obs" load EDGE+
"obs" load "n1" load EDGE+
"obs" load OUT 2 assert-eq
"obs" load phi-pa 20000 assert-eq     \ scope=2 (self + n1)

\ ============================================================
\ k=2..9: progressively add neighbours; verify phi-pa is LINEAR in k.
\ Build with a loop helper so we don't duplicate 8 copies.
\ ============================================================

: add-one-neighbour
  "remaining" load 0 > if
    MARK "obs" load swap EDGE+
    "remaining" load 1 - "remaining" store
    add-one-neighbour
  then ;

: sweep-k ( k -- phi-pa-value )
  "sweep-k" store
  RESET
  MARK "obs" store
  "obs" load "obs" load EDGE+
  "sweep-k" load "remaining" store
  add-one-neighbour
  "obs" load phi-pa ;

\ Verify the linear law: phi-pa(k) = (k+1) · 10000 for k=2..9.
2 sweep-k 30000 assert-eq
3 sweep-k 40000 assert-eq
4 sweep-k 50000 assert-eq
5 sweep-k 60000 assert-eq
6 sweep-k 70000 assert-eq
7 sweep-k 80000 assert-eq
8 sweep-k 90000 assert-eq
9 sweep-k 100000 assert-eq

\ ============================================================
\ Differential test: ANY discontinuity in {phi-pa(k+1) - phi-pa(k)}?
\ For a phase transition, we'd expect this difference to jump non-
\ uniformly.  For a linear measure, the difference is constant.
\ ============================================================

: phi-pa-diff ( k -- delta )
  dup 1 + sweep-k swap sweep-k - ;

2 phi-pa-diff 10000 assert-eq
3 phi-pa-diff 10000 assert-eq
4 phi-pa-diff 10000 assert-eq
5 phi-pa-diff 10000 assert-eq
6 phi-pa-diff 10000 assert-eq
7 phi-pa-diff 10000 assert-eq
8 phi-pa-diff 10000 assert-eq

\ Every differential is exactly L_max=10000.  ZERO variance in
\ slope across k=2..9.  No critical exponent, no discontinuity —
\ phi-pa is exactly linear in scope.

\ ============================================================
\ Self-ref bistability — the ONE non-linear feature of phi-pa.
\ At self-ref = 0: phi-pa = 0 regardless of scope.
\ At self-ref = 1: phi-pa = scope · L_max.
\ This is a binary STEP, not a phase transition in the physics
\ sense (no critical exponent, no continuous-parameter-driven
\ singularity — just a hard switch at self-loop presence).
\ ============================================================

RESET
MARK "obs" store
MARK "n1" store
MARK "n2" store
MARK "n3" store
MARK "n4" store
MARK "n5" store
\ Five out-edges, NO self-loop yet.
"obs" load "n1" load EDGE+
"obs" load "n2" load EDGE+
"obs" load "n3" load EDGE+
"obs" load "n4" load EDGE+
"obs" load "n5" load EDGE+
"obs" load OUT 5 assert-eq
"obs" load phi-pa 0 assert-eq         \ no self-loop → 0

\ Add the self-loop — phi-pa jumps to 50000 in ONE step.
"obs" load "obs" load EDGE+
"obs" load OUT 6 assert-eq            \ self-loop adds to OUT
"obs" load phi-pa 60000 assert-eq     \ (5 originals + 1 self) · 1 · 10000

\ Remove self-loop — phi-pa collapses to 0 again.
"obs" load "obs" load EDGE-
"obs" load phi-pa 0 assert-eq

\ The self-ref switch is a hard binary, not a smooth transition.
\ It cannot serve as a phase-transition order parameter in the
\ physics-of-criticality sense — there is no critical neighbourhood
\ where Φ_PA exhibits diverging correlation length, scaling
\ exponents, or universality-class behaviour.  It is a topological
\ indicator, not a critical phenomenon.

\ ============================================================
\ Honest negative result: NO phase transition in the Φ_PA family
\ as currently defined.
\
\ Why this matters:
\   - Tononi-IIT Φ exhibits a phase transition (Mediano 2019);
\     the substrate-readable Φ_PA shipped in stdlib does not
\   - The four Φ measures (phi-pa, phi-integ, phi-bidir,
\     phi-pa-witness) are all degree-polynomial × self-loop-step
\   - No nonlinear response → no order parameter → no critical
\     exponent → no universality class to identify with anything
\     in the physics-of-consciousness literature
\
\ This is a substrate-derived BOUND on Φ_PA's expressive power.
\ Future measures in the family would need genuine nonlinearity
\ (e.g. mutual information, KL-divergence on substrate-state
\ ensembles) to exhibit phase-transition behaviour.
\ ============================================================

cr
"=== Demo 106 — Φ_PA parametric sweep ===" . cr
cr
